[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering class naming conventions**\n\nIt seems like there's an issue with hsqldb compiling, and I'm concerned about a potential NoClassDefFoundError when resolving JAXBSource if the test runtime is missing jaxb dependencies. I wonder if our custom class names with \"$\" are the culprit, though the rule against \"$\" seems to apply mainly to test class/file names. Nested helper classes might be creating these names. Maybe we should avoid nested helpers and use custom public top-level StAXSource/Result classes instead? That could keep things cleaner!\n\n**Analyzing coverage issues**\n\nI’m thinking we used the exact classes, but maybe the coverage is being ignored because the sourceClass, which equals the base class, uses newInstance. I wonder if branch optimization could be affecting this? It seems for StAXSource, we should be using getConstructor, even if sourceClass equals StAXSource.class. We did use the exact StAXSource.class, so it should be covered. But for StAXResult, the code behaves differently, directly creating a new instance. Hmm, maybe my custom nested classes are causing compilation issues with the $ signs?\n\n**Evaluating dynamic access instrumentation**\n\nI'm wondering about dynamic-access instrumentation possibly excluding reflections when a target class is outside the user code. Wait, does the call site get tracked if the target type is from metadata? Hmm, I think I found that active class dynamic access can scan all calls statically. Coverage is necessary for branches executed regardless of the target. I wonder if our tests aren't running because of the class name; JDBCSQLXMLTest is public.\n\n**Considering the testing process**\n\nI need to think about whether we should compile or run tests ourselves. The developer specifically mentioned we shouldn't do that. Instead, maybe there's a current build report or some problems from an external run after our attempt that could be inspected for results. It seems crucial to avoid running tests on our end for now. I'll look into the reports to see what we can learn from them.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_05680276128df6c50169f981f5bbf0819d8d0ba85a065a89cc\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-YIHntCqgELCMu-maGX1EGIdzPXIatISQD_GUOkJIzZUVdgxgQkBaQEfQcTQwYsW02DkR9zrj_GZl9OMYbU9TgLYYdNwpwKTnVbFZVcl8m7xtpQOuTwxACe2FBbGc2vzkqRLiM48woOBUlds9YDzRN7Jv8YC9yT2bs339e0RWEipzsICkTrbnHwVZr-2vgP1QeobHPVIoTCKjbGHnM_Go7giuqnhkXgcPUocQq7XlGDojEOXdNPCGS31xJYo4KEGY2zREuuHPEozmRMErKOYoWwB5R-Q1S4xOu53lDIyY9SQxtovuljZ9eTjwVke9dsC_HsXo5JFJIr9WljihI-z7Zp77uVxpmxm5WywXcB1VRuTryDVCYCZDnTS6o1Kq0TjGCovvGbxb2EyBx1y-L4e5byN4JGYXrL4NBMJVk2jLMz1DbkI8tnoCCNjpT2tOnkLpmOcPkNg2Shqy6F5uU0t_oXIFx5HNczDgxp1l1tDI0MxQZdn41WW_gEgUK6iCSCDNusBsGt4XP76gce7oiTUQ1p18JpcMZ9gkjKUII3D3X3I1fluP-j_f3BNp_szsSDFTomaJ15qULcEC2X65heP_xsyKJTjI0V0q_vt_ABxV-tUsmdJ-gETqmEDjp8XZIxeWbVajIH3Nkw-VWposkVt0JDzaFCW4IBX5FTsPi0XpmLsAFzKjLVEBPQ5CaJAVglN_ligUo8EoOKE9J3rxZkZI5mdXJhVeWDSPHSVlLCxRKWdKA-nzFlP7SQ7IHdcVC3BKUriwB1iPXtrYYtuMitSsLJDLh4xMvLRlL7gq9I-tAmLBHlYxcNZlKd2AC8ghaytxhYLxLmOm-ozvy5w2W7UJY49p5a50PLphoHw1RmOoMZVR3NYikdqkiPVSQcWLAF5cb9cXsLizQsATQKAh6YELO2nAuZB63eUBP-ZAArX2Y9FNIlejn2flK9y6Hp9_blgS-Cb6jdj4DPEfh2UU4MOTfcQTnquX8Uf11mi1E9mtaK8EMxsZyR0jPcF7TGA8g46FXszY-EaU1By4n9dXXFA0DlU5lYYr0jG0Aeix7lqvx3gqbzLP8fq-dZLL61mjmyRPXgF2OaeyC_vqpujqJFMpPaCwHZXY5JZ7-gklm6QxacqF3sDurze-qGZFPaBcuSXEWstn973bDrIqZai5i_Ot-IUgy150J1cGl_cuukj3AbUdmGxfgPmEZg04EoavOW7zivA5BJ0yxSN9g26kKvX7sZJm2KG_MGA-3sl46qSBZYFfI13g0ijURf0bvY5NDhk1uTY-tHE9Fx15KFVt8w7JlgTr0LAZbe2FMORpCw95leg3saEgDudZvxr0ELVn_lHzPIcnHgVccI855l4G8E_6esMBcMJoDBsF_RvGpEOZEwxm-A8yuWvuehuNN-5nqC_LM95qkpsaIwXSUJpaBxL-y2DhOO5OQUkOe7lWFdHtiiR1OI4j9LT77n0Faofxl7jmRtnLIab7DVPStzk8Ew11iVDDnQ-Mac5jsQykaZLtdPBFBAzaql-H_8QUd38pOgbtEfhqu5CLqsLGmK2K3c3soJDD7A1vEhUJyiFZvjE9smuJNQI7t_9vxJPvQQjRQI20SU0euK7LIOiCLZg8r6Y3fhxSe0-rG4NMD94dxKOyxwpkLmrF59DVrchXsKMOL77EWzGyu